WEBVTT

00:02.035 --> 00:03.403
[ Footsteps echoing ]

00:03.403 --> 00:05.305
I have a great idea for you.
She says,

00:05.305 --> 00:06.640
"One, two, three. Open wide."

00:06.640 --> 00:09.109
And then she tells him
a good job.
Toy: Good job!

00:09.109 --> 00:10.377
I've made you a good offer.

00:10.377 --> 00:12.145
What are you going
to do about it?

00:12.145 --> 00:13.146
♪ Don't stop me,
don't stop me ♪

00:13.146 --> 00:14.181
Cuban: Alright. Come on.
Come on.

00:14.181 --> 00:15.148
♪ Hey, hey, hey ♪

00:15.148 --> 00:16.416
♪ Don't stop me,
don't stop me ♪

00:16.416 --> 00:18.185
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪
[ All cheer ]

00:18.185 --> 00:19.353
♪ Don't stop me,
don't stop me ♪

00:19.353 --> 00:21.388
Lori, oh, my God!
Yeah!

00:21.388 --> 00:24.291
Narrator: It's been
a remarkable 15 years.

00:24.291 --> 00:26.326
♪ Don't stop me now ♪

00:26.326 --> 00:28.128
I'm ready to do
whatever it takes

00:28.128 --> 00:29.429
to blow the lid
off this thing.

00:29.429 --> 00:32.232
Narrator:
The show that is synonymous
with entrepreneurship...

00:32.232 --> 00:33.433
I'm gonna believe in you.
We're gonna ride together.

00:33.433 --> 00:36.270
Whoo-hoo! Now, that's what
I'm talkin' about!

00:36.270 --> 00:37.738
Narrator:
...launched household names...

00:37.738 --> 00:40.440
Scrub Daddy will be scrubbing
in every kitchen in the world.

00:40.440 --> 00:43.443
It allows the user to squat
in a healthy position.

00:43.443 --> 00:46.179
For every pair of socks we sell,
we donate a pair.

00:46.179 --> 00:47.247
Is that comfy, or what?
Look at that.

00:47.247 --> 00:48.382
It's pretty comfy.
Yeah.

00:48.382 --> 00:51.318
You can see and speak
with visitors from anywhere.

00:51.318 --> 00:53.420
Narrator: ...and showcased
business superstars...

00:53.420 --> 00:57.090
[ All gasp, laughter ]

00:57.090 --> 00:58.425
There's only one
Mr. Wonderful.

00:58.425 --> 00:59.593
And thank God for that.
[ Laughs ]

00:59.593 --> 01:01.562
A dream is dope
because it's yours.

01:01.562 --> 01:03.397
I want you to
become a unicorn, too.

01:03.397 --> 01:06.166
Actor to entrepreneur,
I have a lot of respect for you.

01:06.166 --> 01:08.936
Nice.
[ Laughter ]

01:08.936 --> 01:10.170
Sold.
We got a deal.

01:10.170 --> 01:12.205
Narrator: ...and inspired
a generation

01:12.205 --> 01:13.407
of new entrepreneurs.

01:13.407 --> 01:15.342
Our dad invented
the Cup Board Pro.

01:15.342 --> 01:16.543
We are here
to continue his legacy

01:16.543 --> 01:18.345
and make that dream
a reality.

01:18.345 --> 01:21.081
If that's not the American
dream, I don't know what is.

01:21.081 --> 01:21.982
Man: Wow!

01:21.982 --> 01:26.019
♪♪

01:26.019 --> 01:27.220
Narrator: And this season,

01:27.220 --> 01:30.257
exciting, brand-new Guest Sharks
join the Tank.

01:30.257 --> 01:31.758
Michael Rubin is the founder

01:31.758 --> 01:35.462
of the multi-billion dollar
sports retail behemoth Fanatics.

01:35.462 --> 01:38.699
Jason Blum, who changed the
business of the film industry

01:38.699 --> 01:41.635
with his independent
production company, Blumhouse.

01:41.635 --> 01:45.339
And, tonight, Candace Nelson,
the founder of Sprinkles,

01:45.339 --> 01:48.275
revolutionized the cupcake
and created a new category

01:48.275 --> 01:50.110
in the luxury dessert space.

01:50.110 --> 01:51.545
I started Sprinkles
with $200,000,

01:51.545 --> 01:53.413
bootstrapped that
to a national brand,

01:53.413 --> 01:55.449
and I hope the same for you.

01:55.449 --> 01:58.652
Narrator:
A brand-new season begins now.

01:58.652 --> 02:00.420
O'Leary: Remember
the environment we're in.

02:00.420 --> 02:01.688
Venture capital's
dried up.

02:01.688 --> 02:05.158
We're back to where we were when
we started "Shark Tank," 2008.

02:05.158 --> 02:06.259
No money out there.

02:06.259 --> 02:08.328
I have built businesses
worth billions

02:08.328 --> 02:09.429
and billions of dollars.

02:09.429 --> 02:11.531
I can't sit around
waiting all day.

02:11.531 --> 02:14.234
You need to decide if you want
to swim with a Shark

02:14.234 --> 02:15.769
or be eaten by one.

02:16.403 --> 02:20.207
♪ Oh, we pray that
change is coming ♪

02:20.207 --> 02:22.009
Yes! Yes!

02:22.009 --> 02:23.143
Did I hear "royalty"?

02:23.143 --> 02:24.344
Oh, my God.

02:24.344 --> 02:27.247
-Wow.
-That is so cool!

02:27.247 --> 02:28.382
We made this
with no Plan B.

02:28.382 --> 02:29.683
This has to work.
It has to work.

02:29.683 --> 02:32.552
My entrepreneurs will tell you
I'm the best thing

02:32.552 --> 02:34.287
that's ever happened to them
in their life.

02:34.287 --> 02:37.157
This is a bigger picture,
about saving lives.

02:37.157 --> 02:39.226
♪♪

02:39.226 --> 02:42.229
I want to have some fun.
Okay?
[ Laughter ]

02:42.229 --> 02:45.165
This is your moment.
Go, go, go!

02:45.165 --> 02:46.500
Grams?
Woman: Hey.

02:46.500 --> 02:51.171
I got a deal.
I'm so happy for you!

02:51.171 --> 02:53.240
Let's go!
Hoo-hoo-hoo!

02:53.240 --> 02:54.341
♪♪

02:54.341 --> 02:56.009
Greiner: What do you need
from a Shark?

02:56.009 --> 02:57.110
What are you looking for?

02:57.110 --> 02:58.111
Money, honey.

02:58.111 --> 03:00.247
♪ Yes, we're ready ♪

03:00.247 --> 03:08.255
♪♪

03:08.255 --> 03:09.389
Narrator: First in the Tank

03:09.389 --> 03:12.125
is a guiltless version
of a favorite treat.

03:12.125 --> 03:20.367
♪♪

03:20.367 --> 03:23.136
Hey, I'm Ryan,
but he calls me Rodge.

03:23.136 --> 03:24.604
I'm Doug,
but he calls me Dodge.

03:24.604 --> 03:27.674
We're brothers, Rodge and Dodge,
and also business partners.

03:27.674 --> 03:32.145
Sharks, don't we all love
to indulge ourselves in the rich

03:32.145 --> 03:34.448
and satisfactory taste
of delicious chocolate?

03:34.448 --> 03:36.516
But most of those
other chocolates out there,

03:36.516 --> 03:39.386
they're loaded
with calories, sugar, fat.

03:39.386 --> 03:42.422
Well, what if we told you
that we created a chocolate

03:42.422 --> 03:46.359
that has about half the calories
and up to 75% less sugar

03:46.359 --> 03:48.295
than most of the other
chocolates out there --

03:48.295 --> 03:50.030
GATSBY Chocolate.

03:50.030 --> 03:50.530
We make products

03:50.530 --> 03:52.466
that have
mind-blowing flavors,

03:52.466 --> 03:54.134
melt-in-your-mouth texture,

03:54.134 --> 03:55.302
yes, with health in mind,

03:55.302 --> 03:58.338
but, most importantly,
zero compromise on taste.

03:58.338 --> 04:00.607
We call it the Halo Top
of chocolate,

04:00.607 --> 04:04.377
and, Sharks, we can actually
say that, because...

04:04.377 --> 04:06.246
I'm the co-founder
of Halo Top.

04:06.246 --> 04:08.348
No!
Oh, my God.

04:08.348 --> 04:10.050
Oh, my gosh.
That's right, Sharks.

04:10.050 --> 04:11.151
We are the brothers

04:11.151 --> 04:13.620
behind the iconic,
better-for-you ice cream

04:13.620 --> 04:16.356
that is Halo Top,
forged with less calories,

04:16.356 --> 04:18.992
less sugar,
and -- sound familiar? --

04:18.992 --> 04:20.427
no compromise on taste.

04:20.427 --> 04:21.495
After years of hard work,

04:21.495 --> 04:23.163
I led the sale
of the business,

04:23.163 --> 04:25.499
which was the ultimate
cherry on top.

04:25.499 --> 04:27.367
Now, we're poised
to do the same thing

04:27.367 --> 04:29.636
that we did with Halo Top,
but with chocolate.

04:29.636 --> 04:34.341
We're asking for $500,000
for a 5% stake in our company.

04:34.341 --> 04:36.443
I'm out.
So, what do you say,
old sports?

04:36.443 --> 04:38.211
Cheers
to GATSBY Chocolate.

04:38.211 --> 04:39.279
Okay.

04:39.279 --> 04:40.447
In front of you is a variety
of our chocolates.

04:40.447 --> 04:43.116
We know you got to try it
to believe it, so dig in.

04:43.116 --> 04:44.384
And by the way,
I'm just joking.

04:44.384 --> 04:46.686
What's your hero product?
What's the best seller?

04:46.686 --> 04:50.157
The Peanut Butter Madness
is our best seller today.

04:50.157 --> 04:51.525
-Ooh.
-Peanut Butter Madness.

04:51.525 --> 04:53.527
This Fudge Brownie
is really good.

04:53.527 --> 04:55.328
Doug: Oh, yeah.
That is my favorite.

04:55.328 --> 04:57.364
Tastes like brownie batter.
Wow.

04:57.364 --> 04:58.665
This is good.

04:58.665 --> 05:01.501
Are there any
artificial sweeteners in here?

05:01.501 --> 05:04.271
We use allulose as
our main sugar replacement.
Mmm!

05:04.271 --> 05:08.041
But here's something I want
to share that I really love --

05:08.041 --> 05:10.310
190 calories
for this big boy.

05:10.310 --> 05:12.312
For the whole bar.
Where are you selling it now?

05:12.312 --> 05:13.480
So, we're sold nationally
in Walmart,

05:13.480 --> 05:15.215
Safeway, Albertsons,
and Sprouts.

05:15.215 --> 05:17.317
We have more than 6,000
points of distribution.

05:17.317 --> 05:19.553
Oh.
What are your sales
in the last 12 months?

05:19.553 --> 05:23.323
So, sales last year were
about -- just over $2.5 million.

05:23.323 --> 05:24.491
Congrats, man.
That's amazing.

05:24.491 --> 05:26.293
And most of that
was in Q4.

05:26.293 --> 05:28.328
What do you charge for this?
What does it cost you to make?

05:28.328 --> 05:31.231
So, that retails
for $3.99.

05:31.231 --> 05:34.367
That's it?
We sell that
wholesale for $2.70.

05:34.367 --> 05:36.703
It costs us, to make,
about $1.90 a bar today.

05:36.703 --> 05:39.272
That's tough.
So we're running at
about a 35%...

05:39.272 --> 05:40.440
Yeah, that's tough.
...to 40% margin.

05:40.440 --> 05:42.709
However, we have a clear path
to 50%-plus,

05:42.709 --> 05:45.378
and we were
negative margin last year.
You can fix that.

05:45.378 --> 05:48.014
Yes.
Nelson: Obviously, you've done
really well for yourselves.

05:48.014 --> 05:49.216
What do you need a Shark for?

05:49.216 --> 05:50.450
Yeah.
Well, the main thing is,

05:50.450 --> 05:51.651
if you had asked me that
a couple years ago,

05:51.651 --> 05:54.421
I probably would have thought
that I didn't need you.

05:54.421 --> 05:57.157
But I romanticized
the early days

05:57.157 --> 05:59.326
of startup life
way too much.

05:59.326 --> 06:01.628
And there's a missing puzzle
piece here where we need help,

06:01.628 --> 06:03.430
because we have
national distribution

06:03.430 --> 06:05.298
without
national awareness.

06:05.298 --> 06:06.633
That's the problem. Yeah.
Where does the name come from?

06:06.633 --> 06:09.603
Yeah. That's exactly
what I was going to say.
I am so lost on the name.

06:09.603 --> 06:12.305
Yeah, yeah. So, we read that
"The Great Gatsby," the book,

06:12.305 --> 06:14.341
was going into what's called
the public domain,

06:14.341 --> 06:16.509
and we thought, you know,
that would be a great brand name

06:16.509 --> 06:19.145
to play on premium,
decadence, indulgence.

06:19.145 --> 06:20.447
Greiner: But it doesn't fit.
I don't love it.

06:20.447 --> 06:23.250
I know. And you know what?
I agree with you 100%.

06:23.250 --> 06:25.619
I look at this,
I knew it was a chocolate bar.

06:25.619 --> 06:28.355
But beyond that,
I didn't know what this was.

06:28.355 --> 06:31.324
Calories per bar,
the 190's really big.

06:31.324 --> 06:33.460
But reading this,
I missed it.

06:33.460 --> 06:34.694
And then the name GATSBY,

06:34.694 --> 06:38.198
and there's a martini
in the end for the "Y."

06:38.198 --> 06:39.599
I was thinking
that this was somehow,

06:39.599 --> 06:41.401
like, liquor-flavored
chocolate.

06:41.401 --> 06:42.435
Mm-hmm.
Doug: That's fair.

06:42.435 --> 06:45.138
And I lost --
I didn't get what it was.

06:45.138 --> 06:47.173
You forecast sales
for this year,

06:47.173 --> 06:49.209
and you're not making
any money yet, are you?

06:49.209 --> 06:51.778
So, no free cash flow,
and sales for this year,

06:51.778 --> 06:55.315
we expect them to actually
approach just under $2 million.

06:55.315 --> 06:57.017
How much did you lose?

06:57.017 --> 07:00.120
We lost $3.5 million
last year.

07:00.120 --> 07:03.223
So, $500,000 for 5%

07:03.223 --> 07:05.358
imputes a $10 million valuation.
Correct.

07:05.358 --> 07:07.394
Sales are $2 million...
Correct.

07:07.394 --> 07:09.162
...with no free cash flow.

07:09.162 --> 07:10.930
See any problem with that?

07:10.930 --> 07:11.631
In context, I don't.

07:11.631 --> 07:13.500
When you think about
the credibility of who we are

07:13.500 --> 07:14.668
and what we've done
at Halo Top...
You're paying for him.

07:14.668 --> 07:16.536
...when you think about where
we've taken this product.

07:16.536 --> 07:18.371
Yeah,
but, I mean, look.
We have a patent-pending
formula, as well.

07:18.371 --> 07:21.374
With all due respect, and you
guys have done an amazing job,

07:21.374 --> 07:23.209
this is "Shark Tank."
Yes.

07:23.209 --> 07:25.045
I don't pay retail
for anything.

07:25.045 --> 07:27.047
John: You know,
here's my thing.

07:27.047 --> 07:27.614
You're very credible.

07:27.614 --> 07:30.116
I don't have any problem
with the valuation.

07:30.116 --> 07:31.351
I just add no value here.

07:31.351 --> 07:35.388
I would be calling you,
asking you for advice.

07:35.388 --> 07:38.224
So, good luck, man.
I'm out.

07:38.224 --> 07:39.426
Thank you.
Thank you.

07:39.426 --> 07:42.595
What possessed you, after
you had such an incredible ride

07:42.595 --> 07:46.366
with Halo Top, to go back in
and start another company?

07:46.366 --> 07:48.835
I'm so glad you asked that.
Stupidity.

07:48.835 --> 07:51.237
[ Laughter ]

07:51.237 --> 07:52.439
It's amazing
how arrogant you get

07:52.439 --> 07:53.606
after you sell
a company, right?

07:53.606 --> 07:55.442
True.
Because you think
you know everything, yeah.

07:55.442 --> 07:57.510
You forget, and you romanticize
those early days

07:57.510 --> 07:59.479
and you forget the grind,
and, like...
Absolutely.

07:59.479 --> 08:01.915
...we've got the product
to where it is today

08:01.915 --> 08:03.049
that you've tried.

08:03.049 --> 08:04.551
We're in
enough distribution.

08:04.551 --> 08:07.387
The last thing we're missing
is the spark.

08:07.387 --> 08:10.056
Greiner: I really like it.
I'll make you an offer.

08:10.056 --> 08:12.258
It's a little bit risky, right?

08:12.258 --> 08:15.695
Sure.
I would do it
as half as equity...

08:15.695 --> 08:19.566
Okay.
...and half as
a short-term loan.

08:19.566 --> 08:22.035
What are the terms
of the loan?
At 6%. I'm going to be nice.

08:22.035 --> 08:24.037
Okay. Okay.
A nice loan shark.

08:24.037 --> 08:25.205
[ Both chuckle ]

08:25.205 --> 08:28.008
And I would do it --
I want 20%.

08:28.008 --> 08:30.276
Ooh!
I want 20%, though.

08:30.276 --> 08:32.145
But I'll be in it
to win it with you.

08:32.145 --> 08:33.646
I will help you redesign
this packaging.

08:33.646 --> 08:37.417
I will be a voice.
I'm your demo, and I love this.

08:37.417 --> 08:39.652
Do you care
about the equity more?

08:39.652 --> 08:43.323
In other words, Lori's
asking you for 20% equity.

08:43.323 --> 08:46.426
What I would say is
100% of zero dollars is zero.

08:46.426 --> 08:48.661
[ Laughs ]
A true entrepreneur, right?
Nelson: Yes.

08:48.661 --> 08:50.330
You guys have been
through it.
You get it.

08:50.330 --> 08:52.032
$500,000.
Okay.

08:52.032 --> 08:53.233
All venture debt.

08:53.233 --> 08:56.169
Okay.
And I'll do it
for 12% equity.

08:56.169 --> 08:57.604
Okay.
Mm.

08:57.604 --> 09:01.007
So, you know...
Well, are you not
entertaining my offer?

09:01.007 --> 09:01.441
I'm just curious.

09:01.441 --> 09:02.509
Yes, absolutely.
Yes.

09:02.509 --> 09:04.644
Because if that's
more exciting to you...

09:04.644 --> 09:07.714
This product is delicious.
It actually...
Thank you.

09:07.714 --> 09:11.117
It's really good, yeah.
I am surprised
by how delicious it is.

09:11.117 --> 09:13.253
Mm-hmm.
A few things, though.

09:13.253 --> 09:16.623
One, the calories
so emblazoned

09:16.623 --> 09:20.460
on this package --
Millennial and Gen Z,

09:20.460 --> 09:22.729
they consider this
toxic diet culture,

09:22.729 --> 09:26.032
and I think there's
gonna be a backlash
against that, a little bit.

09:26.032 --> 09:27.700
So I'm concerned
about that.

09:27.700 --> 09:31.137
When I saw this packaging,
I knew there were men behind it.

09:31.137 --> 09:34.340
This does not appeal
to me as a woman.

09:34.340 --> 09:36.776
So you desperately need Lori
for your rebrand.

09:36.776 --> 09:41.181
Thank you.
And I wish you the best because
this is delicious, but I'm out.

09:41.181 --> 09:44.350
Alright, guys,
are you open to 20% equity?

09:44.350 --> 09:46.052
Yes.
Oh, you are?

09:46.052 --> 09:46.553
For the right deal.

09:46.553 --> 09:48.521
However,
I would like to tie

09:48.521 --> 09:51.090
to the face of the brand-type
partnership...

09:51.090 --> 09:53.092
-Mm.
-Ooh. That's expensive.

09:53.092 --> 09:54.160
...where you
become the face

09:54.160 --> 09:55.528
of the new brand
that you help us create.

09:55.528 --> 09:58.431
For me, that's Ryan Reynolds
and Mint Mobile,

09:58.431 --> 10:00.700
that's The Rock
and his tequila.

10:00.700 --> 10:03.303
That's the creator-led
brands.
Mm-hmm. Yeah.

10:03.303 --> 10:04.471
That's what
they're having at exit,

10:04.471 --> 10:05.605
because they're
the face of that,

10:05.605 --> 10:08.374
and essentially makes it
zero dollars of marketing spend.

10:08.374 --> 10:10.276
So, very open to 20%.

10:10.276 --> 10:13.279
If that's what you want,
then give me 25%.

10:13.279 --> 10:16.349
♪♪

10:16.349 --> 10:18.218
Okay.
We'd be open to that.

10:18.218 --> 10:19.819
Done.

10:19.819 --> 10:23.623
Can I hear --
Did Mark have an offer?
No, it's done.

10:23.623 --> 10:25.458
No, Mark has an offer,
but I don't want to be...
It's done.

10:25.458 --> 10:27.427
My brand's too big
to be face of a brand, right?

10:27.427 --> 10:28.695
I'm sorry. So, for you,
I would ask,

10:28.695 --> 10:32.398
would you be open to helping us
find a face of the brand,

10:32.398 --> 10:33.500
in addition to come in?
Oh. Uh-oh.

10:33.500 --> 10:35.301
You know what?
You know what?

10:35.301 --> 10:42.976
♪♪

10:46.079 --> 10:48.414
♪♪

10:48.414 --> 10:50.416
Narrator:
Two Sharks are out.

10:50.416 --> 10:54.287
Ryan and Doug have two offers
on the table from Lori and Kevin

10:54.287 --> 10:55.522
for their low-calorie,

10:55.522 --> 10:57.624
yet delicious
chocolate brand, GATSBY.

10:57.624 --> 11:00.326
But their hesitation
in accepting Lori's offer

11:00.326 --> 11:02.495
may cost them the deal.

11:02.495 --> 11:05.465
Would you be open to helping us
find a face of the brand

11:05.465 --> 11:07.333
in addition to come in?
Oh. Uh-oh.

11:07.333 --> 11:08.601
You know what?
You know what?

11:08.601 --> 11:12.305
I'm sorry. I don't just
put my face on anything.

11:12.305 --> 11:16.242
I'm very, very selective about
what I would do that with.

11:16.242 --> 11:18.545
A minute ago,
I was going to do it at 25%.

11:18.545 --> 11:21.981
Now I'm back to the original
deal at -- it's 20%.

11:21.981 --> 11:26.219
Will you tie any vesting to
that equity?
Though I won't give you a
hard guarantee of my face

11:26.219 --> 11:28.221
on any package
beyond this.

11:28.221 --> 11:30.123
So, how many people
have an offer, please?

11:30.123 --> 11:31.591
Lori, you have
that offer at 20%.

11:31.591 --> 11:33.293
Come here.
Kevin, what's your offer?

11:33.293 --> 11:34.627
O'Leary:
I made just a very clean offer.

11:34.627 --> 11:40.466
I look at it and say,
"You need as much awareness

11:40.466 --> 11:42.235
to the product
as you possibly get."

11:42.235 --> 11:45.104
Yes.
So, my offer
is pretty straight.

11:45.104 --> 11:46.472
I'm going to look at it
and say...

11:46.472 --> 11:48.241
Alright, you're done
with him. Alright.
Yoo-hoo! Hello.

11:48.241 --> 11:50.009
[ Laughter ]

11:50.009 --> 11:50.610
So, we were talking.

11:50.610 --> 11:52.278
So, now we have a different
offer to give you.

11:52.278 --> 11:56.249
Alright.
So, we're going
to give you the $500,000.

11:56.249 --> 11:59.452
Okay.
We're doing it half as a loan...

11:59.452 --> 12:02.822
Okay.
...and we're doing it half
as equity for 20%.

12:02.822 --> 12:07.994
Okay.
But when we hit
the first $10 million in sales,

12:07.994 --> 12:09.429
we each get 5% more.

12:09.429 --> 12:12.198
So, the kicker comes -- If
we get to $10 million in sales,

12:12.198 --> 12:13.399
that's another 10%.
Sure.

12:13.399 --> 12:17.136
Right.
And then if we get to
$20 million in sales, right...

12:17.136 --> 12:21.107
We get another 5% each.
Each. Right?

12:21.107 --> 12:23.176
Okay.

12:23.176 --> 12:25.378
My only issue
with the 10 and the 20

12:25.378 --> 12:26.579
is I can't sell
the company at the end.

12:26.579 --> 12:29.282
If we wanna exit this, I need
those to be a little higher.

12:29.282 --> 12:30.383
Okay.
Oh, so the threshold.

12:30.383 --> 12:32.085
Yeah, the threshold --
Yeah, I need the threshold.

12:32.085 --> 12:33.319
Because if we can get to...

12:33.319 --> 12:34.554
50 is typically where...

12:34.554 --> 12:36.756
...50,
we're cooking with gas.
Right.

12:36.756 --> 12:38.558
We can do some fun things
at 50.
Right. Right. Right. Right.

12:38.558 --> 12:40.727
So do it at 25 and then 50.
No, because it's going
from 10.

12:40.727 --> 12:43.496
No. So we want it at 10. Yeah.
The first trigger can be 10.

12:43.496 --> 12:46.165
Okay.
The first trigger's 10.
It would be
the second trigger, 50,

12:46.165 --> 12:48.301
because then we can sell.
Okay.

12:48.301 --> 12:50.069
Done.
Done. [ Laughs ]

12:50.069 --> 12:52.205
Whoo!
Greiner: Oh, my God.

12:52.205 --> 12:53.406
Congrats, guys.
I'm so excited.

12:53.406 --> 12:55.241
[ All speaking indistinctly ]

12:55.241 --> 12:57.343
What a great partnership.
Oh! I always wanted to meet

12:57.343 --> 13:00.013
who was behind Halo Top.
I appreciate it.

13:00.013 --> 13:01.180
Congratulations, you guys.

13:01.180 --> 13:02.115
-Thank you, guys.
-Thank y'all.

13:02.115 --> 13:04.050
Yeah.
Doug: Thank you.

13:04.050 --> 13:05.218
♪♪

13:05.218 --> 13:06.219
[ Both laugh ]

13:06.219 --> 13:09.022
Agh!

13:09.022 --> 13:10.323
Let's go, baby.

13:10.323 --> 13:11.457
Doug: We have
a missing puzzle piece,

13:11.457 --> 13:13.326
and we almost are on
our last leg here.

13:13.326 --> 13:15.395
So, this was
super impactful,

13:15.395 --> 13:16.529
where had we not come
on the "Tank,"

13:16.529 --> 13:17.864
had we not gotten
a deal done,

13:17.864 --> 13:20.633
I don't know that
GATSBY Chocolate exists
beyond this year,

13:20.633 --> 13:23.503
so it is unbelievably meaningful
and really adds

13:23.503 --> 13:26.706
some much-needed momentum
to the brand.

13:27.240 --> 13:28.441
Nelson: This may surprise
a lot of people,

13:28.441 --> 13:30.610
but I was born
in Jakarta, Indonesia.

13:30.610 --> 13:33.413
My dad worked for
an American company overseas,

13:33.413 --> 13:35.515
so I was constantly moving
as a child.

13:35.515 --> 13:38.551
My mom was a great hostess
and cook.

13:38.551 --> 13:41.554
She spent hours teaching me
the science of baking,

13:41.554 --> 13:44.324
and I remember
just being mesmerized by it.

13:44.324 --> 13:45.458
But I was raised to believe

13:45.458 --> 13:46.693
I should pursue
a corporate path.

13:46.693 --> 13:49.529
I never thought I could pursue
baking as a career.

13:49.529 --> 13:53.332
I went to Wesleyan University.
I majored in economics.

13:53.332 --> 13:56.269
After graduating college,
I went out to San Francisco

13:56.269 --> 13:57.537
to work at an investment bank.

13:57.537 --> 14:01.174
But in 2001,
the Internet market crashed,

14:01.174 --> 14:03.042
and I was left without a job.

14:03.042 --> 14:04.310
That led to an epiphany

14:04.310 --> 14:06.379
that I wanted to proclaim
my love for baking

14:06.379 --> 14:09.315
and attend pastry school
instead of business school.

14:09.315 --> 14:12.385
After pastry school, I started
this custom-cake business.

14:12.385 --> 14:14.320
But these cakes
took forever to make,

14:14.320 --> 14:16.222
and it just wasn't
a scalable business,

14:16.222 --> 14:18.725
and my banking brain
started kicking in again.

14:18.725 --> 14:21.461
Sprinkles is the world's first
cupcakes-only bakery.

14:21.461 --> 14:24.163
My goal was to take
the simple cupcake

14:24.163 --> 14:25.431
and make it
into a true luxury,

14:25.431 --> 14:27.633
something that people
could even give as a gift.

14:27.633 --> 14:30.503
I was panicked on opening day
that no one would show up,

14:30.503 --> 14:33.272
but when we opened,
we had a line out the door.

14:33.272 --> 14:35.208
Eight months in,
I picked up the phone,

14:35.208 --> 14:37.009
and the producer
on the other end said,

14:37.009 --> 14:38.244
"Oprah loves your cupcakes."

14:38.244 --> 14:40.513
The next morning, Oprah Winfrey
basically delivered

14:40.513 --> 14:43.683
a love letter about our cupcakes
to the entire world.

14:43.683 --> 14:48.254
From that point on, Sprinkles
became a worldwide brand name.

14:48.254 --> 14:50.523
Today, Sprinkles has
over 50 locations

14:50.523 --> 14:53.292
across the U.S.,
and even internationally.

14:53.292 --> 14:54.761
Sprinkles was
a category creator,

14:54.761 --> 14:58.231
but within a few years,
we were in a crowded market,

14:58.231 --> 14:59.599
and we knew we needed
to innovate again.

14:59.599 --> 15:01.634
I started thinking about
what it would look like

15:01.634 --> 15:04.604
if you could get a cupcake
anytime day or night, and boom,

15:04.604 --> 15:06.539
the idea for
the cupcake ATM was born.

15:06.539 --> 15:09.175
I wrote a New York Times
best-selling cookbook

15:09.175 --> 15:10.376
called "The Sprinkles
Baking Book,"

15:10.376 --> 15:13.579
and now a best-selling business
book called "Sweet Success."

15:13.579 --> 15:16.315
Make sure our whipped cream
is nice and fluffy.

15:16.315 --> 15:19.418
In 2014, my husband and I
decided to step away

15:19.418 --> 15:21.521
from the business operationally,
bring on a partner

15:21.521 --> 15:23.656
who could help accelerate
the growth of Sprinkles

15:23.656 --> 15:26.392
and allow us to spend more time
with our growing family.

15:26.392 --> 15:28.161
The last thing I thought
was that I would

15:28.161 --> 15:29.495
get right back
into the food business.

15:29.495 --> 15:32.632
But one bite of pizza
changed all of that.

15:32.632 --> 15:36.235
Pizzana is bringing the best
of Italy to the United States.

15:36.235 --> 15:39.539
Daniele Uditi was a passionate
and talented chef

15:39.539 --> 15:42.108
who I wanted to partner with
and bring his incredible

15:42.108 --> 15:43.543
artisanal pies to America.

15:43.543 --> 15:46.012
I love taking foods
people think they know

15:46.012 --> 15:47.513
and giving them a fresh spin.

15:47.513 --> 15:50.349
I did it with cupcakes, and
we're doing it again with pizza.

15:50.349 --> 15:52.952
I plan to scale Pizzana
across the U.S.

15:52.952 --> 15:54.320
Willy!

15:54.320 --> 15:56.222
I love that "Shark Tank"
celebrates the spirit

15:56.222 --> 15:57.523
of entrepreneurship.

15:57.523 --> 16:00.426
Being an entrepreneur
has been so meaningful to me.

16:00.426 --> 16:03.429
It's really taught me
what I'm capable of.

16:03.429 --> 16:07.466
I think I'm most proud of
veering off the expected path.

16:07.466 --> 16:11.037
I took a risk, and I was
courageous and bet on myself.

16:11.037 --> 16:12.271
No one believed in my idea,

16:12.271 --> 16:14.140
but I doggedly
listened to my gut

16:14.140 --> 16:16.008
and saw my vision to life.

16:16.008 --> 16:22.648
♪♪

16:25.017 --> 16:29.388
♪♪

16:29.388 --> 16:31.324
Narrator:
Next up are best friends

16:31.324 --> 16:33.359
who believe
they have the perfect pairing

16:33.359 --> 16:36.128
for one of America's
favorite foods.

16:36.128 --> 16:42.101
♪♪

16:42.101 --> 16:43.269
Kevin: Hello, Sharks.
What's up?

16:43.269 --> 16:44.170
-Hello.
-Hi.

16:44.170 --> 16:45.238
My name is Kevin Klein.

16:45.238 --> 16:47.406
And I'm his best friend
of over 30 years,

16:47.406 --> 16:50.176
Joshua Green
from Los Angeles, California.

16:50.176 --> 16:52.245
We're here today
seeking $200,000

16:52.245 --> 16:53.246
and your friendship

16:53.246 --> 16:56.482
for 7.5% of the greatest
company ever.

16:56.482 --> 16:58.317
Mm.
Now, Sharks,
what if I told you

16:58.317 --> 17:01.120
that our product could
instantly make you smarter...

17:01.120 --> 17:02.255
More attractive.

17:02.255 --> 17:05.391
Younger.
And even regrow hair?

17:05.391 --> 17:07.193
Well, guess what?

17:07.193 --> 17:08.561
It can't do any
of those things.

17:08.561 --> 17:11.264
[ Laughter ]
Sorry, Mr. Wonderful.

17:11.264 --> 17:13.199
There are just
some things in life

17:13.199 --> 17:14.700
that will never
get any better.

17:14.700 --> 17:17.536
But there are some things
in life that can get better,

17:17.536 --> 17:19.472
like pizza
when you pair it with...

17:19.472 --> 17:20.740
Pie Wine.
Pie Wine.

17:20.740 --> 17:24.577
Pie Wine is a sweet, sparkling,
easy-drinking canned table wine

17:24.577 --> 17:26.612
that goes great
with your favorite slice.

17:26.612 --> 17:31.083
That's why we say Pie Wine
is the OG pizza wine.
AKA...

17:31.083 --> 17:32.451
Pizza's new side piece.
AKA...

17:32.451 --> 17:35.655
It puts
the "ahh" in "pizza."
AKA...

17:35.655 --> 17:37.523
Dude, that's it.
We're out of slogans.

17:37.523 --> 17:40.493
We knew we had to reimagine
and reintroduce to the masses...
[ Laughter ]

17:40.493 --> 17:42.728
...what pizza-loving Italians
have known for generations --

17:42.728 --> 17:46.232
That pizza goes best with
a sweet, slightly bubbly wine,

17:46.232 --> 17:48.334
traditionally known
as a Lambrusco.
Mm.

17:48.334 --> 17:49.969
That's why we say...

17:49.969 --> 17:51.037
"Born in Italy.

17:51.037 --> 17:53.205
Perfected in California."

17:53.205 --> 17:55.107
So, Sharks,
who's ready to meet

17:55.107 --> 17:56.375
the greatest thing
to happen to pizza

17:56.375 --> 17:58.010
since the pepperoni...

17:58.010 --> 18:00.012
And turn any old pizza...

18:00.012 --> 18:01.380
...into a pizza...

18:01.380 --> 18:05.384
Together: ...party,
with Pie Wine!

18:05.384 --> 18:06.419
-Whoo-hoo!
-Good job.

18:06.419 --> 18:08.120
Alright. Salute!
Salute!

18:08.120 --> 18:09.155
Salud.

18:09.155 --> 18:11.424
Wow, you guys understood
the assignment.

18:11.424 --> 18:12.692
Well done. Nice pitch.
Thank you.
We do what we can.

18:12.692 --> 18:14.427
Of course, it'd be rude
if we were drinking alone,

18:14.427 --> 18:17.163
so we brought you
all three of our SKUs to try.
"White."

18:17.163 --> 18:18.731
The red
is our Sweet Za.

18:18.731 --> 18:21.467
The blue is
our White Crisp.
Classic Crisp.

18:21.467 --> 18:24.236
And the black is
our World Famous Red.

18:24.236 --> 18:25.671
Let's stand up.
Nelson: Okay.

18:25.671 --> 18:28.975
Very big tradition for many,
many years here in the Tank.
This is "Shark Tank" tradition.

18:30.142 --> 18:32.044
Un, deux, trois.

18:32.044 --> 18:34.246
All: Chevaliers du Tastevin!

18:34.246 --> 18:36.215
Hey!
Mm.

18:36.215 --> 18:38.651
Ahh!

18:40.019 --> 18:41.487
Mmm!

18:41.487 --> 18:43.255
It's pretty darn good.
It's good!

18:43.255 --> 18:46.058
Thank you. We brought you
some pizza, by the way.

18:46.058 --> 18:47.360
O'Leary:
They're very, very good.

18:47.360 --> 18:50.463
I've never had wine
with pizza,

18:50.463 --> 18:52.531
and I didn't realize
it's so delicious.

18:52.531 --> 18:54.967
We're thinking, there's never
been an official drink of pizza.

18:54.967 --> 18:58.037
Now, they've tried to tell us
to drink beer with pizza.
Some people think it's beer.

18:58.037 --> 18:58.604
Yeah,
but beer with pizza...

18:58.604 --> 19:00.373
It's terrible.
...flavor profiles don't work.

19:00.373 --> 19:02.341
I agree with that. Too filling.
I need something with bubbles,

19:02.341 --> 19:04.443
so I think of a cola...
Exactly.

19:04.443 --> 19:06.212
...and I never
thought that...
But you're a man.

19:06.212 --> 19:07.279
You're a grown man.

19:07.279 --> 19:08.280
Yeah.
So, boom.

19:08.280 --> 19:09.615
There you go.
I like that.
Exactly.

19:09.615 --> 19:11.417
Greiner: Here's what's
confusing for me.

19:11.417 --> 19:14.487
I pick up the can.
I don't understand what this is.

19:14.487 --> 19:20.559
It says "World Famous Red,"
"Pizza & New Side Piece," "Pie."

19:20.559 --> 19:22.528
And I'm looking at this,
and I'm like,

19:22.528 --> 19:24.397
"This has something
to do with pizza,

19:24.397 --> 19:26.198
but I don't know what it is."

19:26.198 --> 19:27.500
I do find it really confusing,

19:27.500 --> 19:28.734
and I think
it's going to hurt you.

19:28.734 --> 19:32.104
Well, why don't we find out
if that issue is valid or not?

19:32.104 --> 19:33.272
What are your sales?
Yeah.

19:33.272 --> 19:34.974
So, we launched
two weeks ago.

19:34.974 --> 19:35.441
-Oh.
-Oh!

19:35.441 --> 19:36.642
Okay.
Two weeks ago.

19:36.642 --> 19:41.080
And here's the good news --
As of -- Early as today...

19:41.080 --> 19:43.315
We have distribution
in eight states.

19:43.315 --> 19:45.151
We've already had
distributor commitments

19:45.151 --> 19:48.220
for between $300,000
and $400,000 already,

19:48.220 --> 19:49.655
and we're talking
to 18 other states.

19:49.655 --> 19:52.358
Nevada --
Well, first of all,
congratulations.

19:52.358 --> 19:54.460
Congratulations.
But no sell-through date, right?

19:54.460 --> 19:57.329
Happy day. What does that mean
for dollars?

19:57.329 --> 19:59.432
$300,000 to $400,000
in wholesale dollars.

19:59.432 --> 20:00.633
Okay.
And we expect that

20:00.633 --> 20:03.402
to be well north of
a half a million in 30 days.

20:03.402 --> 20:05.304
And what we're projecting
for the first six months

20:05.304 --> 20:06.372
is about $1.5 million.

20:06.372 --> 20:09.208
In the end of the year,
about $6.5 million.

20:09.208 --> 20:10.409
Something I'm really
curious about --

20:10.409 --> 20:11.610
You started this
two weeks ago.

20:11.610 --> 20:14.180
This can't possibly be
your full-time job. Is it?

20:14.180 --> 20:15.581
We've been working on this
for two years.

20:15.581 --> 20:19.118
I actually host a morning radio
show on KROQ in Los Angeles.
Oh.

20:19.118 --> 20:20.553
Oh!
I knew you were familiar.

20:20.553 --> 20:23.022
I'm a radio guy.
I'm looking at you,
and I'm like,

20:23.022 --> 20:24.123
"I've seen your face."

20:24.123 --> 20:25.291
I host
the morning radio show.

20:25.291 --> 20:26.559
I've been doing morning radio
for about 20 years.

20:26.559 --> 20:28.160
So, I'm in
the fun business.

20:28.160 --> 20:29.228
-Nice.
-Yes, you are.

20:29.228 --> 20:30.496
This guy's the smart one.
I'm the smart ass.

20:30.496 --> 20:32.431
That's why we kind of
complement each other.

20:32.431 --> 20:34.333
My background is
I went to law school,

20:34.333 --> 20:35.501
got a master's
in accounting.

20:35.501 --> 20:38.137
I worked at bulge bracket
investment banking,

20:38.137 --> 20:40.272
and now I help run
one of the largest

20:40.272 --> 20:43.843
spatial computing video game
companies in the country.

20:43.843 --> 20:44.310
Wow.
Wow.

20:44.310 --> 20:45.444
I'm the CFO
of the company.

20:45.444 --> 20:47.379
I came in to help turn
around the business.

20:47.379 --> 20:49.215
So, guys, this is
a side hustle for you.

20:49.215 --> 20:52.118
No, it's not a side hustle.
I sold my 401(k) to do this.

20:52.118 --> 20:53.419
Like, I wish
I could say --
Oh, wow.

20:53.419 --> 20:55.221
How much have you invested
in the business?

20:55.221 --> 20:56.555
We've invested
over $300,000.

20:56.555 --> 20:58.724
Between the two of you?
So, are you 50/50 partners?
Correct.

20:58.724 --> 21:01.193
We're 50/50 partners.
You put in
the same amount of money?

21:01.193 --> 21:02.361
He's put in
a little more than me.

21:02.361 --> 21:04.463
What have you done?
[ Scoffs ]
What have I done?

21:04.463 --> 21:08.000
I ended up talking to my wife,
we sold the house...

21:08.000 --> 21:08.701
-Oh.
-Wow.

21:08.701 --> 21:10.402
...so that we could use
some of that money...
Damn!

21:10.402 --> 21:11.537
So you're all in?
Wow.

21:11.537 --> 21:14.006
Green: We're invested.
Yeah, we're all in, big time.

21:14.006 --> 21:15.141
What are their margins?

21:15.141 --> 21:16.675
So, it costs us $1.50
right now to make.

21:16.675 --> 21:20.146
We have a plan to get it down
to $1.25 with more production,

21:20.146 --> 21:22.114
and we'll sell it
to distributors for $3.25.

21:22.114 --> 21:23.382
$3.25 a can.

21:23.382 --> 21:26.986
And then it would sell,
if you were at Ralphs
or Kroger, whatever,

21:26.986 --> 21:28.454
around $5, $5.50.

21:28.454 --> 21:31.157
There are other
canned sparkling wines.

21:31.157 --> 21:32.591
There are.
Who is your biggest competitor?

21:32.591 --> 21:35.628
Because I feel like the market
is really saturated.

21:35.628 --> 21:38.531
Looking at comps, Bev is one of
the comps that came out, and...

21:38.531 --> 21:41.133
Bev just got sold.
...Bev just got sold.

21:41.133 --> 21:42.468
They went out with
a pre-money valuation,

21:42.468 --> 21:44.637
before they had any sales,
at $7 million.

21:44.637 --> 21:47.606
We're doing a discount because
the truth is, we want a Shark.

21:47.606 --> 21:51.310
And I just want to circle back
to, like, what started this.

21:51.310 --> 21:52.545
I've known him since
we were 8 years old.

21:52.545 --> 21:56.048
I love the guy.
He's a big part of my life.

21:56.048 --> 21:57.416
I have
an amazing wife and kids.

21:57.416 --> 21:59.418
The last four years
have been a little challenging

21:59.418 --> 22:02.154
because my wife, unfortunately,
has metastatic cancer...

22:02.154 --> 22:03.055
-Oh, no.
-No.

22:03.055 --> 22:03.622
...and doing something

22:03.622 --> 22:07.226
with your best friend
is really exciting,

22:07.226 --> 22:08.627
and I want
to teach my kids.

22:08.627 --> 22:11.630
Hard work is so important.
Like, nothing's given.

22:11.630 --> 22:14.433
It's not a side hustle.
I zeroed out my 401(k).

22:14.433 --> 22:17.269
I don't think about, like,
oh, saving for the future.

22:17.269 --> 22:18.470
I wanted to do a business
with him

22:18.470 --> 22:21.106
because I love him and
I want to see him successful.

22:21.106 --> 22:22.608
I'm in business.
He hasn't been.

22:22.608 --> 22:25.477
But I want him to see
some of the successes I've had,

22:25.477 --> 22:29.215
and I love the idea, and I
